<section class="hero">
  <p class="hero-label">Framework</p>
  <h1>Universal Microservices Architecture</h1>
  <p class="hero-bio">A portable, contract-driven execution model for distributed systems. Business logic that runs where it makes sense — browser, edge, cloud, AI pipeline — without rewriting it every time.</p>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <p class="section-label">What is UMA?</p>
  <p style="font-size:0.95rem;color:var(--mid);line-height:1.8;max-width:560px;">UMA separates business logic from runtime environment. Instead of rewriting the same logic for browser, backend, edge, and AI pipelines, you write it once as a portable, self-contained unit — a Universal Microservice — and deploy it wherever it makes sense.</p>
  <p style="font-size:0.95rem;color:var(--mid);line-height:1.8;max-width:560px;margin-top:1rem;">Each service is governed by a contract that defines what it does, what it needs, and what it guarantees. The contract is the interface. The implementation can run in any compliant runtime — Rust, WASM, browser, edge worker, or AI pipeline.</p>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <p class="section-label">Core Principles</p>
  <div class="concept-list">
    <div class="concept-item">
      <h2>Contract-first</h2>
      <p>Every service defines its interface, dependencies, and guarantees in a machine-readable contract before implementation begins. The contract is the source of truth — not the code.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-item">
      <h2>Runtime-agnostic</h2>
      <p>Business logic compiled to WebAssembly runs unchanged across browser, Node, Deno, Cloudflare Workers, and AI pipelines. The execution environment is a deployment decision, not an architectural one.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-item">
      <h2>Composable by design</h2>
      <p>Services are discovered, validated, and composed at runtime through a capability registry. Systems built with UMA can adapt to new requirements without structural rewrites.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-item">
      <h2>AI-navigable</h2>
      <p>Every service has declared intent, explicit dependencies, and a lifecycle-aware contract. AI agents can reason about what a system does, why each part exists, and how to extend it safely.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <p class="section-label">The problem it solves</p>
  <p style="font-size:0.95rem;color:var(--mid);line-height:1.8;max-width:560px;">The same business logic gets rewritten three, four, five times across browser, backend, edge, and AI pipelines. Most architectures assume the runtime too early and teams pay that cost forever — in maintenance, in drift, in onboarding time, and in the inability to adapt. UMA eliminates the assumption. Logic and runtime are separate concerns from the start.</p>
</section>

