<section class="hero">
  <p class="hero-label">Framework</p>
  <h1>Contract-Driven AI Development</h1>
  <p class="hero-bio">The missing foundation in AI-assisted software development. AI tools can describe what code does — but not why. Contracts fill that gap.</p>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <p class="section-label">What is C-DAD?</p>
  <p style="font-size:0.95rem;color:var(--mid);line-height:1.8;max-width:560px;">Contract-Driven AI Development (C-DAD) is a framework where verifiable contracts — not prompts, not comments, not documentation — define how humans, AI systems, and runtimes collaborate to build software.</p>
  <p style="font-size:0.95rem;color:var(--mid);line-height:1.8;max-width:560px;margin-top:1rem;">The difference between a specification and a contract is verifiability. A specification describes intent. A contract enforces it. C-DAD makes every piece of software behaviour a first-class, machine-readable, lifecycle-aware contract.</p>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <p class="section-label">Core Principles</p>
  <div class="concept-list">
    <div class="concept-item">
      <h2>Contracts over code</h2>
      <p>AI tools automate structure. They cannot automate understanding. Contracts declare why software behaves as it does — the rationale, the constraints, the governance rules. This is the layer AI tools need to reason about systems, not just describe them.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-item">
      <h2>Verifiable, not just readable</h2>
      <p>Contracts in C-DAD are immutable units of record with explicit lifecycle states: Draft, Active, Deprecated, Retired. They carry provenance, validation results, and audit trails. They can be signed, distributed, and checked — not just read.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-item">
      <h2>Hybrid governance</h2>
      <p>Not everything should be automated. C-DAD defines explicit handoff points where human judgment is required — and makes those points visible in the contract itself. Automation handles the routine. Humans govern the consequential.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="concept-item">
      <h2>Machine-first authoring</h2>
      <p>Contracts are authored as machine-readable manifests with human-friendly documentation generated from them — not the other way around. The machine-readable layer is the source of truth. The narrative is derived.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <p class="section-label">The problem it solves</p>
  <p style="font-size:0.95rem;color:var(--mid);line-height:1.8;max-width:560px;">AI coding tools can write code that looks right. They cannot know if it is right — because right is determined by intent, and intent was never declared. C-DAD makes intent a first-class citizen of the development process. Every behaviour has a contract. Every contract has a reason. Every reason is machine-readable.</p>
</section>

